**Claim 1.** A computer-implemented scientific measurement analysis system comprising:

- a physical measurement apparatus configured to acquire, by interaction with a physical target, at least one measurement record and to output said at least one measurement record to the storage described below;
- a storage configured to hold a plurality of measurement records, each said record being a directed entry comprising an identifier of a producing measurer, an identifier of a target entity, an identifier of a property, a numerical value, a method identifier, and a source tag taking one of two predetermined values, the first value indicating that the record was produced by physical interaction with the target and the second value indicating that the record was produced by computation, wherein the storage operates on an append-only basis such that a subsequent record with the same (producing measurer, target, property) composite key overwrites the prior record in the storage while the prior record is preserved in an append-only event log external to the storage;
- a convergence analyser configured to group said records by (target, property) pair and, for each group containing two or more records, to compute a relative-spread measure of the numerical values and to classify said group as one of *converged*, *tension*, *divergent*, or *single* according to said measure against predetermined thresholds;
- a measurer-correlation analyser configured to compute, for each measurer, the counts of its groups in each said classification and to classify said measurer as a *systemic-crack* source when two or more of its groups are *divergent* or *tension*, as a *systemic-opening* source when two or more of its groups are *converged* and none are *divergent* or *tension*, and as a *local-crack* source when exactly one of its groups is *divergent* or *tension*;
- a population-decomposition analyser configured to determine, for a (target, property) group classified as *tension* or *divergent* by the convergence analyser, whether the distribution of its numerical values admits a decomposition into two or more components under a Gaussian-mixture model selected by a Bayesian-information-criterion improvement threshold, subject to a minimum-component-size guard and a minimum-inter-component-separation guard, and, when such a decomposition is found, to propose a split of the identifier of the target entity of said group into two or more sub-identifiers with each record assigned to exactly one sub-identifier, said split being effected on the storage through rewriting of the target-entity identifier field of each record;
- a feedback-signal generator configured to emit, for each measurer classification and each proposed identifier split, a machine-readable feedback signal encoding the analyser's output; and
- a feedback-signal interface configured to route said feedback signal to an actor configured to annotate the storage or to cause a modification of how subsequent measurement records are acquired by the physical measurement apparatus,

**wherein** the source tag is a field on each directed entry and is the sole basis for invoking (i) the echo-chamber classifier of claim 2, when present, and (ii) the pattern-requirement rule of claim 4, when present, such that physical-interaction records and computational records share the storage schema and are classified under the same grouping and relative-spread computations without reference to whether the producing measurer is a physical instrument or a computational measurer, while the source tag alone gates downstream logic that distinguishes physical-interaction from computational evidence, and

**wherein** the system does not comprise (i) an ontology layer assigning semantic types to the entities, the properties, or the methods identified in said records, (ii) a separate object-type or property-type registry external to the storage, or (iii) a separate model-card, model-registry, or model-configuration record external to the storage for characterising a producing measurer, such that any characterising attribute of a producing measurer that is held by the system is held as a directed entry in the storage under the same six-field schema as a measurement record of a physical target; and wherein all semantic labelling, if performed, is performed external to the claimed system and is not consumed by the convergence analyser, the measurer-correlation analyser, or the population-decomposition analyser.

**Claim 2.** The system of claim 1, further comprising an echo-chamber classifier configured to:

- identify, among groups formed by the convergence analyser, a subset of groups in which at least two records within the group are produced by distinct computational measurers bearing distinct method identifiers, and to process each group in said subset as follows;
- when said group contains at least one record produced by a physical measurement apparatus and the convergence analyser's classification of said group is *converged*, emit a confirmed-echo-chamber signal identifying said group;
- when said group contains at least one record produced by a physical measurement apparatus and the convergence analyser's classification of said group is *tension* or *divergent*, emit a refuted-echo-chamber signal identifying said group; and
- when said group contains no record produced by a physical measurement apparatus, emit an untested-echo-chamber signal identifying said group;

wherein the feedback-signal interface is further configured to route each of said confirmed-, refuted-, and untested-echo-chamber signals to the actor, and wherein the measurer-correlation analyser of claim 1 is further configured to accept, as an optional input, a per-measurer trust weight derived from an accumulation over the event log of prior refuted-echo-chamber signals attributed to each measurer, and to attenuate the contribution of a measurer to its own measurer classification in inverse proportion to said trust weight.

**Claim 8a.** The system of claim 1, further comprising an instrument-comparison analyser configured to:

- identify a first measurer and a second measurer, each represented as a target entity in the storage and each having one or more directed entries written against said target entity by a further measurer, said directed entries being of the same six-field schema as directed entries recording measurements of physical targets;
- compute, from said directed entries, a first attribute set for said first measurer and a second attribute set for said second measurer, each said attribute set comprising the property identifiers of the directed entries written against the respective measurer as target;
- compute a symmetric difference between said first attribute set and said second attribute set;
- hold, for each of one or more target properties of interest, a sensitivity set comprising property identifiers on which the respective target property is accuracy-dependent;
- determine, for each said target property of interest, whether the intersection of said sensitivity set and said symmetric difference is non-empty; and
- emit, for each target property for which said intersection is non-empty, a machine-readable divergence-prediction signal identifying said first measurer, said second measurer, and said target property,

wherein said divergence-prediction signal is routed through the feedback-signal interface of claim 1 to the actor, and

**characterised in that** the instrument-comparison analyser produces its output entirely from directed entries in the storage and from the sensitivity sets, such that modification of an attribute-set entry for either measurer in the storage causes a corresponding modification of subsequent divergence-prediction outputs without modification of the analyser's instructions.

**Claim 10.** The system of claim 9, further comprising a marker-propagation analyser configured to:

- assign to each inference step a marker taking one of at least two structurally distinguishable forms according to the convergence-status annotation of said step, including a first form for steps annotated *converged* and a second form for steps annotated *divergent* or *tension*;
- propagate said markers along edges of a graph whose nodes are admissible operational-mechanism identifiers and whose edges connect identifiers that co-occur in the list of at least one inference step, with a per-hop decay factor;
- detect, at any shared operational-mechanism identifier at which markers from two or more distinct inference steps coincide with accumulated intensity above a threshold, a collision event; and
- classify each collision event as an *opening-collision* when all contributing markers are of the first form, as a *crack-collision* when all contributing markers are of the second form, and as a *bridge-collision* when contributing markers include markers of both forms, and to emit a collision signal identifying the shared operational-mechanism identifier, the classification, and the inference-step identifiers of the contributing steps.

**Claim 13.** A computer-implemented scientific measurement analysis method comprising:

- acquiring, by a physical measurement apparatus interacting with a physical target, at least one measurement record;
- storing the acquired record together with further measurement records in a storage, wherein each record is a directed entry comprising an identifier of a producing measurer, an identifier of a target entity, an identifier of a property, a numerical value, a method identifier, and a source tag taking one of two predetermined values distinguishing physical-interaction records from computation-produced records, wherein storage is append-only with composite-key overwrite and an external append-only event log;
- grouping said records by (target, property) pair;
- for each said group containing two or more records, computing a relative-spread measure of the numerical values and classifying said group as *converged*, *tension*, *divergent*, or *single*;
- for each measurer, counting its groups in each classification and classifying said measurer as *systemic-crack*, *systemic-opening*, *local-crack*, or none;
- for each (target, property) group classified as *tension* or *divergent*, testing whether the distribution of its numerical values admits a Gaussian-mixture decomposition into two or more components subject to minimum-size, BIC-improvement, and minimum-separation guards, and, when it does, proposing a split of the identifier of the target entity and effecting said split on the storage;
- emitting a machine-readable feedback signal encoding each measurer classification and each proposed split; and
- routing said feedback signal to an actor configured to annotate the storage or to cause a modification of how subsequent records are acquired by the physical measurement apparatus,

**wherein** the method does not involve maintaining (i) an ontology layer assigning semantic types to the entities, the properties, or the methods, (ii) a separate object-type or property-type registry external to the storage, or (iii) a separate model-card, model-registry, or model-configuration record external to the storage for characterising a producing measurer, such that any characterising attribute of a producing measurer that is represented in the method is represented as a directed entry in the storage under the same six-field schema as a measurement record of a physical target.

**Claim 14.** A computer-implemented scientific knowledge analysis method comprising:

- holding an operational-mechanism vocabulary of language-independent numerical identifiers, each identifier carrying a Boolean admissibility flag distinguishing identifiers naming a physical or computational instrument mechanism from identifiers naming a theoretical commitment or target assumption;
- rejecting, at insertion time, any identifier whose admissibility flag indicates a theoretical commitment or target assumption;
- holding a plurality of inference steps, each inference step comprising a claim descriptor, a convergence-status annotation, and a list of admissible operational-mechanism identifiers; and
- processing said inference steps under a reading discipline that does not admit any identifier whose admissibility flag indicates a theoretical commitment or target assumption, such that any inference drawn from shared identifiers across distinct inference steps reflects shared instrument mechanism and does not reflect shared theoretical framing.

**Claim 15.** The method of claim 14, further comprising:

- assigning to each inference step a marker of one of at least two structurally distinguishable forms according to its convergence-status annotation;
- propagating said markers along edges of a graph whose nodes are admissible operational-mechanism identifiers, with a per-hop decay factor and a fixed hop-count limit;
- detecting, at any shared identifier at which markers from two or more distinct inference steps coincide above a threshold, a collision event; and
- classifying said collision event as an *opening-collision*, *crack-collision*, or *bridge-collision* according to the marker forms contributing.

**Claim 16.** The method of claim 13, further comprising:

- identifying, among (target, property) groups containing at least two records from distinct computational measurers bearing distinct method identifiers, those groups containing at least one physical-interaction record and those not, and classifying each such group as *confirmed*, *refuted*, or *untested* according to the agreement of the computational records with the physical-interaction record(s) when present;
- computing, from the event log of claim 13, a decay-weighted per-measurer trust weight derived from prior refuted classifications attributed to each measurer;
- attenuating, by said trust weight, the contribution of each measurer to its own systemic classification; and
- routing a feedback signal encoding the classifications and the attenuated systemic labels to the actor of claim 13.

**Claim 16a.** The method of claim 13, further comprising:

- representing each of a plurality of measurers as a target entity in the storage and storing, as directed entries written against each said measurer by a further measurer, property-identified attribute values, said directed entries being of the same six-field schema as directed entries recording measurements of physical targets;
- for a first measurer and a second measurer each so represented, computing a first attribute set comprising the property identifiers of the directed entries written against the first measurer as target, and a second attribute set comprising the property identifiers of the directed entries written against the second measurer as target;
- computing a symmetric difference between said first attribute set and said second attribute set;
- holding, for each of one or more target properties of interest, a sensitivity set comprising property identifiers on which the respective target property is accuracy-dependent;
- determining, for each said target property of interest, whether the intersection of said sensitivity set and said symmetric difference is non-empty;
- emitting, for each target property for which said intersection is non-empty, a machine-readable divergence-prediction signal identifying said first measurer, said second measurer, and said target property; and
- routing said divergence-prediction signal to the actor of claim 13,

**wherein** the emitting step produces its output entirely from directed entries in the storage and from the sensitivity sets, such that modification of an attribute-set entry for either measurer in the storage causes a corresponding modification of subsequent divergence-prediction outputs without modification of instructions of the method.

**21.** The system of claim 20, wherein each said structured pointer comprises:

- a composite coupling key identifying a specific (measurer, target, property) triple in the storage;
- an event identifier identifying a specific event in the append-only event log of claim 1; and
- a content-hash value, said content-hash value being computed by applying a cryptographic hash function to a canonical serialization of the coupling entry at the storage state that resulted from the specific event identified by the event identifier;

and wherein the system is further configured, upon a subsequent retrieval operation referencing said structured pointer, to recompute the content-hash value from the storage state at the event identified by the event identifier and to compare the recomputed value against the stored content-hash value.

**23.** The system of claim 22, further comprising a classifier configured to emit, for each cyclic subgraph whose typed cycle annotation indicates that the spectral-radius metric meets or exceeds the predetermined threshold, a dynamical-signature annotation, said dynamical-signature annotation taking one of at least four predetermined values, the four said values distinguishing:

- a first signature characterized by convergence of the subgraph's measurement records toward a value predicted by the subgraph's prediction records;
- a second signature characterized by drift of the subgraph's measurement records toward boundary values of the property range;
- a third signature characterized by alteration of the subgraph's target entity in response to the subgraph's action records; and
- a fourth signature characterized by optimization of action-record selection against the subgraph's prediction records.

**24.** The system of claim 22, further comprising a second classifier configured to:

- receive as input a coupling group consisting of one or more records whose source tag carries the third predetermined value and whose structured pointers reference a hypothesis inference step, said records representing an adoption of the hypothesis inference step by automated actors;
- analyze, over said coupling group and subsequent records in the storage, dynamics of convergence of measurement records against values predicted by the hypothesis inference step; and
- emit a mode annotation, said mode annotation taking one of at least four predetermined values distinguishing:
  - a first mode characterized by absence of systematic convergence or divergence;
  - a second mode characterized by convergence of measurements toward hypothesis predictions with a direction of causation from measurement to hypothesis;
  - a third mode characterized by convergence of measurements toward hypothesis predictions with a direction of causation from hypothesis to subsequent measurement; and
  - a fourth mode characterized by divergence of measurements away from hypothesis predictions subsequent to a period of convergence.

**26.** The system of claim 20, further comprising a variety-monitoring analyzer configured to:

- compute, for a target entity in the storage, an empirical entropy over a rolling window of measurement values;
- compute, for an automated actor producing action records referencing the target entity, a declared-variety value equal to a cardinality-derived function of the automated actor's most recent structured pointer set;
- compare the empirical entropy against the declared-variety value; and
- upon the empirical entropy exceeding the declared-variety value by a predetermined margin:
  - emit a requisite-variety-deficit event in the append-only event log;
  - suspend production of further action records from said automated actor with reference to said target entity; and
  - maintain said suspension until one of: an update to the automated actor's structured pointer set is committed, or a manual-override event is committed to the event log by an authorized operator.

**28.** The system of claim 1, wherein the marker-propagation analyzer is further configured to:

- compute, prior to marker propagation, a decomposition of the inference-step dependency graph into strongly-connected components;
- construct a condensation graph, said condensation graph being the directed acyclic graph obtained by contracting each strongly-connected component to a single node; and
- propagate markers on the condensation graph rather than on the inference-step dependency graph directly;

and wherein, for each strongly-connected component of the inference-step dependency graph that contains more than one node, the system is further configured to route the internal dynamics of the component to a fixed-point solver configured to compute performatively-stable states on the component under predetermined contraction conditions.

**29.** The system of claim 22, further comprising a counterfactual generator configured to:

- receive, for a cyclic subgraph whose spectral-radius metric meets or exceeds the predetermined threshold, a set of historical action records comprising said cyclic subgraph;
- compute, for each said historical action record, a gradient value, said gradient value being the partial derivative of the spectral-radius metric of the cyclic subgraph with respect to the parameters of said historical action record, obtained via an adjoint computation traversing the cyclic subgraph;
- select, from said historical action records, a perturbation set comprising at most a predetermined maximum number of action records, said perturbation set being those historical action records whose gradient values have the largest absolute magnitude among all the gradient values computed;
- construct, for each action record in the perturbation set, one or more counterfactual histories in which the action record is replaced by an alternative action record; and
- rank the counterfactual histories by the reduction in the cyclic subgraph's spectral-radius metric that results when the counterfactual history is substituted for the actual history.

**30.** The system of claim 25, further comprising an experimental-design generator configured to:

- receive a coupling group classified by the convergence analyzer of claim 1 as divergent or under tension;
- enumerate a plurality of candidate measurement actions, each said candidate measurement action being specified by a proposing automated actor's structured pointer set, a target entity identifier, a property identifier, and a predicted uncertainty computed via the uncertainty-propagation layer of claim 25;
- compute, for each said candidate measurement action, an expected-information-gain value derived from a reduction in posterior uncertainty over the coupling group's property value that would result if the candidate measurement action were performed and yielded a measurement record with the predicted uncertainty; and
- emit a ranked list of the candidate measurement actions, said ranked list being sorted by the expected-information-gain value.
